From the printer's records, it is known that 2.4 million stamps were printed using the
first plate, and only 900 thousand using the second plate. One \tete cliche occurred at position 80 of the second plate, so it can be estimated that only six thousand \tete pairs were printed.

This value was principally used for the local rate within Paris from July 1850 until June 1853, so it is rarely found in pairs. However, a 1 franc 30 centimes rate to the United States gave rise to the only unique \tete variety of France. Figure 2 shows a March 1852 double-weight cover front from Paris to New Orleans. Its 2 francs 60 centimes franking includes the only known (unused or used) \tete pair of the 1850 15 centimes stamp. 

